  <article xml:id="session1wks">
    <title>MATH 152 Hands-On, Grades Up</title>
    <introduction>
    <p>
     For workspace between exercises, print this worksheet or download to your device by clicking the printer icon.
    </p>
    </introduction>
<!--START TYPING CONTENT FOR SESSION BELOW HERE-->
<worksheet>
    <title> Session #10 (Sections 10.1 &amp; 10.2)</title><!-- SECTION 10-->
    <p>
      Directions: Answer each of the following as best you can. Feel free to discuss your thoughts about the questions with some peers around you. 
      For additional practice problems and explanations, refer to the Math 152 textbook which can be found in your WebAssign Course.
    </p>
    <page>
      <paragraphs>
        <title>Getting Warmed Up and Focused</title>
      </paragraphs>
      <p>For #1-8 below, read the statement and then circle "true" if the statement is correct and "false" if the statement is not correct.</p>
    <exercise>
      <statement><!-- #1 -->
        <p>
         <alert>True or False </alert>: The path represented by the parametric equations 
         <m>x(t)=\cos(t), \ y(t)=\sin(t)</m>, where <m>\displaystyle 0\leq t \leq \frac{3\pi}{2}</m>, is a circle 
         of radius 1, with initial point at <m>(1,0) </m>, terminal point at <m>(0,-1)</m>, and the path follows a counterclockwise direction.
        </p>
        
      </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
      <statement><!-- #2 -->
        <p>
        <alert>True or False </alert>: The path represented by the parametric equations <m>x(t)=\sin(t), \ y(t)=\cos(t)</m>, where 
        <m>\displaystyle 0\leq t \leq \frac{3\pi}{2}</m>, is a circle of radius 1, with initial point at <m>(0,1)</m>, terminal point at <m>(-1,0)</m>, 
        and the path follows a clockwise direction.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement><!-- #3 -->
        <p> 
        <alert>True or False </alert>: The paths represented by <m>x_1(t)=\sin(t), \ y_1(t)=\cos(t)</m> and <m>x_2(t)=\cos(t), \ y_2(t)=\sin(t)</m> 
        are the same paths.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement><!-- #4 -->
        <p>
         <alert>True or False </alert>: The path represented by <m>x(t)=\sin(2t),\ y(t)=\cos(2t)</m>, where <m>0\leq t \leq2\pi</m>, 
         starts at <m>(0,1)</m> and moves in the clockwise direction twice around a circle centered at <m>(0,0)</m> with a radius  of 1.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement><!-- #5 -->
        <p>
         <alert>True or False </alert>: Given <m>x(t)=t^2</m> and <m>y(t)=t^3-3t</m>, the slope of the tangent for any value of <m>t</m> is 
         <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}=\frac{3t^2-3}{2t}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement><!-- #6 -->
        <p> <alert>True or False </alert>: 
         Given <m>x(t)=4\cos(t)</m> and <m>y(t)=3\sin(t)</m>, the slope of the tangent line at 
         <m>\displaystyle t=\frac{3\pi}{4}</m> is <m>\displaystyle\frac{4}{3}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement><!-- #7 -->
        <p>
         <alert>True or False </alert>: The curve defined by  <m>x(t)=4\cos(t)</m>, <m>y(t)=3\sin(t)</m> has a horizontal tangent line 
         at <m>\displaystyle t=\frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

<exercise workspace="1 in">
      <statement><!-- #8 -->
        <p>
         <alert>True or False </alert>: The curve defined by  <m>x(t)=4\cos(t)</m>, <m>y(t)=3\sin(t)</m>, has a vertical tangent line at 
         <m>\displaystyle t=\frac{\pi}{2}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
    </page>

    
    
      <page>
      <paragraphs>
        <title>Let Us Get Our Hands On</title>
      </paragraphs>
    <exercise workspace="9 in" number="1">
      <statement><!-- #1 -->
        <p>Sketch the graph of <m>x(\theta) = 2\cos(2\theta), \quad y(\theta) = 8\sin(2\theta)</m> for <m>\displaystyle { 0 \le \theta \le \frac{\pi}{2} }</m> and include the direction of the curve on your graph. 
          Describe in words the path as <m>\theta</m> increases from <m>0</m> to <m>\displaystyle \pi/2</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  </page>

  <page>
    <exercise workspace="9 in" number="2">
      <statement><!-- #2 -->
        <p>Match the parametric equations with their corresponding graphs and give reasons for your choices.
        <ol>
          <li><p> The parametric equations <m>x(t)=\sin(3t),\ y(t)=3\cos(t)</m> match Graph #<m>\underline{\qquad\qquad}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p> The parametric equations <m>x(t)=3\sin(t),\ y(t)=3\cos(t)</m> match Graph #<m>\underline{\qquad\qquad}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p> The parametric equations <m>x(t)=t^{2}-2t,\ y(t)=t</m> match Graph #<m>\underline{\qquad\qquad}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p> The parametric equations <m>x(t)=\sin(3t),\ y(t)=\cos(3t)</m> match Graph #<m>\underline{\qquad\qquad}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p> The parametric equations <m>x(t)=3\sin(t),\ y(t)=\cos(3t)</m> match Graph #<m>\underline{\qquad\qquad}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p> The parametric equations <m>x(t)=t^{2}-2t,\ y(t)=t^{2}</m> match Graph #<m>\underline{\qquad\qquad}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p> The parametric equations <m>x(t)=t^{2}-2t,\ y(t)=\sqrt{t}</m> match Graph #<m>\underline{\qquad\qquad}</m>.</p></li>
          <li><p> The parametric equations <m>x(t)=t^{2}-2t,\ y(t)=t^{3}</m> match Graph #<m>\underline{\qquad\qquad}</m>.</p></li>
        </ol>
        <table>
          <title>Graphs to Match with Equations Above</title>
          <tabular halign="center">
            <row>
              <cell>Graph I<image source="3sin(t)3cos(t).png"> <description><p>
                A graph of a circle centered at the origin with radius 3. The circle intersects the y-axis at <m>(0,3)</m> and <m>(0,-3)</m> 
                and the x-axis at <m>(3,0)</m> and <m>(-3,0)</m>. 
              </p></description></image></cell>
              <cell>Graph II<image source="sin(3t)3cos(t).png"><description><p>
                
              </p></description></image> </cell>
              <cell>Graph III<image source="3sin(t)cos(3t).png"><description><p>
               Parametric curve forming three horizontal lobes, one centered at the origin and one on each side. Each lobe resembles a small loop extending outward along the x-axis. 
              </p></description></image> </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Graph IV<image source="sin(3t)cos(3t).png"><description><p>
               A graph of a circle centered at the origin with radius 1. The circle intersects the y-axis at <m>(0,1)</m> and <m>(0,-1)</m> 
                and the x-axis at <m>(1,0)</m> and <m>(-1,0)</m>. 
              </p></description></image> </cell>
              <cell>Graph V<image source="t^2-2tandsqrt(t).png"><description><p>
              Curve beginning near <m>(0,1)</m>, rising slowly and flattening as it moves right. The graph bends gently upward with increasing x.  
              </p></description></image> </cell>
              <cell>Graph VI<image source="t^2-2tandt.png"><description><p>
               Curve starting near <m>(-1,1)</m>, bending smoothly outward as x increases, and forming a wide arc that gradually rises and falls. The graph extends rightward with a shallow slope. 
              </p></description></image> </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>Graph VII<image source="t^2-2tandt^2.png"><description><p>
                Curve starting near <m>(-1,1)</m>, bending leftward and then rising steeply as x increases. The graph widens quickly, forming an opening shape that grows upward and to the right.
              </p></description></image> </cell>
              <cell>Graph VIII<image source="t^2-2tandt^3.png"><description><p>
              A parametric curve that decreases rapidly and is concave up near <m>t=-1</m>. Then it changes to concave down it moves right from <m>(0,0)</m>, crossing the x-axis near <m>t=1</m> and continuing 
              to decrease.   
              </p></description></image> </cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </page>
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="3.5 in" number="3">
      <statement><!-- #3 -->
        <p>  Find the length of the curve <m>x=t^{3}, \quad y=t^{2}</m> for <m>0\le t \le 1</m>.  
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
    <exercise workspace="3.5 in" number="4">
      <statement><!-- #4 -->
        <p> Find the length of the curve <m>x = e^{t} + e^{-t}, \quad y=5-2t</m> for <m>0\le t\le 1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  </page>
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="8 in" number="5">
      <statement><!-- #5 -->
        <p> Find the length of one arch of the cycloid <m>\displaystyle x = 3(\theta-\sin(\theta)), y = 3(1-\cos(\theta))</m>. A graph of the cycloid is provided below.
        </p>
        <p>
          {Hint}:  <m>\displaystyle \sin\left(\frac{\theta}{2}\right) = \pm \sqrt{\frac{1-\cos(\theta)}{2}}\implies \sin^{2}\left(\frac{\theta}{2}\right) = \frac{1-\cos(\theta)}{2}\implies 2 \sin^{2}\left(\frac{\theta}{2}\right) = 1-\cos(\theta)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <image source="cycloid.png" width="50%"><description><p>
            Cycloid curve consisting of repeating arches. Each arch begins at the x-axis, rises to a rounded peak 6 units above the x-axis, and returns to the x-axis at regularly spaced intervals.
          </p></description></image>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  </page>
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="3.5 in" number="6">
      <statement><!-- #6 -->
        <p> At what point(s) on the curve <m>x = t^{2}+1, \quad y=t^{3}-1</m> does the tangent line have slope <m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{2}</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
    <exercise workspace="3.5 in" number="7">
      <statement><!-- #7 -->
        <p> Set up, but do not evaluate, the integral that gives area of the surface obtained by rotating the curve <m>x =t\sqrt{t},\  y=t^{2}</m> for <m>0 \le t \le 1</m> the axes indicated below. 
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
              about the <m>y</m>-axis.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
              about the <m>x</m>-axis.

              </p>
            </li>
          </ol> 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  </page>

  <page>
    <exercise workspace="8 in" number="8">
      <statement><!-- #8 -->
        <p> Find the area enclosed by the cycloid <m>\displaystyle x(t)=t-\sin(t), \  y(t)=1-\cos(t)</m> when <m>\displaystyle 0 \leq t \leq 2\pi</m>, and the <m>x</m>-axis.</p>
        <p><em>Hint:</em> <m>\displaystyle \cos(2x)=\cos^{2}(x)-\sin^{2}(x)</m> and <m>\displaystyle \sin^{2}(x)+\cos^{2}(x)=1</m>. Putting these together we get 
        <md>  \cos(2x)=2\cos^{2}(x)-1 \implies \frac{\cos(2x)+1}{2}=\cos^{2}(x).</md> This will make integrating <m>\cos^{2}(t)</m> a bit easier.</p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  </page>

  <page>
  <exercise workspace="2.5 in" number="9">
      <statement><!-- #9 -->
        <p> Find the area enclosed by the loop of the curve <m>\displaystyle x(t)=t^{2},\ y(t)=t^{3}-3t</m>.</p>
        <p>
        <image source="t^2_(t^3-3t).png" width="50%"><description>
          <p>
          Parametric curve forming a loop that is symmetric about the x-axis. The right most point is <m>(0,0)</m> and the curve crosses itself at <m>(3,0)</m>. To the right of <m>(3,0)</m>, the
          graph extends infinitely upward and infinitely downward, maintaining symmetry to the x-axis.
          </p> 
          </description></image>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise workspace="4 in" number="10">
      <statement><!-- #10 -->
        <p> Find the surface area of the object obtained by rotating <m>\displaystyle x(t)=9+2t^{2},\ y(t)=4t</m> for <m>0\leq t \leq 2</m> about the <m>x-</m>axis.</p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
   </page>

  <page>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Now Grades Go Up</title>
      </paragraphs>
 <exercise workspace ="3.5 in" number="1">
  <statement><!-- #1 -->
    <p>
      If <m>\displaystyle x(t)=\sin(9t)</m> and <m>\displaystyle y(t)=\cos(9t)</m>, then which of the follow represents <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}=</m>?
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle -\tan(9t)</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle \cot(9t)</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle 81\sec^{2}(9t)</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle 9\tan(t)</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle \tan(9t)</m></p> </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
 </exercise>
 <exercise workspace ="3.5 in" number="2">
  <statement><!-- #2 -->
    <p>Set up, but do not evaluate, the integral that gives the surface area of the object obtained by rotating 
     <m>\displaystyle x(t)=1+\ln(5+t^{2}),\ y(t)=2t-2t^{2}</m>, where <m>\displaystyle 0 \leq t \leq 2</m>, about the <m>y-</m>axis.
     You may assume that the curve traces out exactly once for the given range of <m>t</m>.
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{2} 2\pi\left(1+\ln(5+t^{2})\right)\sqrt{\frac{4t^2}{(5+t^2)^2}+(2-4t)^{2}}\ dt</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{2} 2\pi\left(1+\ln(5+t^{2})\right)\sqrt{\frac{2t}{5+t^2}+2-4t}\ dt</m></p></li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{2} 2\pi r\sqrt{\frac{4t^2}{(5+t^2)^2}+(2-4t)^{2}}\ dt</m> </p></li>
          <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{2} 2\pi(2t-2t^{2})\sqrt{\Big(1+\ln(5+t^{2})\Big)^{2}+\big(2t-2t^{2}\big)^{2}}\ dt</m> </p></li>
          <li> <p> <m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{2} 2\pi(2t-2t^{2})\sqrt{\frac{4t^2}{(5+t^2)^2}+(2-4t)^{2}}\ dt</m> </p></li>
        </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
 </exercise>
</page>

<page>
 <exercise workspace ="3.5 in" number="3">
  <statement><!-- #3 -->
    <p>
      The integral that  correctly calculates  the length of the curve defined by <m>x(t)=t^{3}+t,\  y(t)=t^{5}-t</m> for <m>0 \leq t \leq 1</m> is<m>\underline{\qquad\qquad}</m>.
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{1} (t^{3}+t)\sqrt{2+6t^{2}-t^{4}+25t^{8}}\  dt</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{1} (t^{5}-t)(3t^{2}+1)\ dt</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{1} 2 \pi r\sqrt{3t^{2}+5t^{4}}\ dt</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{1} \sqrt{2+6t^{2}-t^{4}+25t^{8}}\ dt</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{1} (t^{5}-t)\sqrt{3t^{2}+5t^{4}}\ dt</m></p> </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
 </exercise>

 <exercise workspace ="3.5 in" number="4">
  <statement><!-- #4 -->
    <p>
      Find the points on the curve <m>\displaystyle x(t)=t^{2},\ y(t)=t^{2}-2t</m> where the tangenet line is horizontal.
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle (x,y)=(2,1)</m></p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle (x,y)=(1,1)</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle (x,y)=(1,2)</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle (x,y)=(1,-1)</m> </p> </li>
          <li> <p><m>\displaystyle (x,y)=(2,-1)</m> </p> </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
 </exercise>
</page>

<page>
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Helpful Formulas</title>
    </paragraphs>
    <p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>If the curve is traced out once by the parametric equations <m>x=f(t)</m> and <m>y=g(t)</m>, <m>\alpha \leq t \leq \beta</m> then we can calculate the area 
      under the curve with the formula <m>\displaystyle A=\int_{\alpha}^{\beta}g(t)\ f'(t) \ dt</m>.</p></li>
  
  <li>
    <p>
      If a curve <m>C</m> is described by the parametric equations <m>x=f(t)</m>, <m>y=g(t)</m>, <m>\alpha \leq t \leq \beta</m>, where <m>f'(t)</m> and <m>g'(t)</m>
  are continuous on <m>[\alpha,\beta]</m> and <m>C</m> is traversed exactly once as <m>t</m> increases from <m>\alpha</m> to <m>\beta</m>, then
    </p>
  ≈
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
      the length, <m>L</m>, of <m>C</m> is given by <m>\displaystyle L=\int_{\alpha}^{\beta}\sqrt{\left(\frac{dx}{dt}\right)^{2}+\left( \frac{dy}{dt}\right)^{2}}\ dt</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
      the surface area is give by <m>\displaystyle S=\int_{\alpha}^{\beta}2\pi r\sqrt{\left(\frac{dx}{dt}\right)^{2}+\left( \frac{dy}{dt}\right)^{2}}\ dt</m>.
If the curve is rotated about the <m>x-</m>axis, then <m>g(t)\geq0</m> and <m>r=y(t)</m>.
If the curve is rotated about the <m>y-</m>axis, then <m>f(t)\geq 0</m> and <m>r=x(t)</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</li>
      </ul>  
     </p>
      </page>
</worksheet>

  </article>

</pretext>